Based on the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

instruct the GAD Focal Person to (i) ensure that total allocation for GAD PPAs to be implemented during the year shall conform with the actual amount provided for GAD in the approved budget; (ii) undertake proper planning in the procurement of goods and supplies for the implementation of the GAD PPAs; (iii)be guided by COA Circular 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012 to avoid disallowance/s relative to irregular, unnecessary, excessive, extravagant and unconscionable (IUEEU) expenditures; (iv) refrain from procuring goods or supplies on reimbursement basis; (v) submit justification on the change of the mode of procurement from SVP to Direct Contracting despite absence of a revised APP and/or BAC Resolution recommending the use of Direct Contracting; (vi) if the project/s may be related to the COVID-19 emergency response, the reason for not resorting to Emergency Procurement under Republic Act (R.A.) No. 11469 or the Bayanihan to Heal As One Act; and (vii) henceforth, strictly observe the provision of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to promote transparency, economy and efficiency in the procurement process;

through its GAD Focal Point System (GFPS), exhaust all available resources for the collection and processing of data requirements of the GAD Database;  


request the SB to establish a clear-cut guidelines, policies and procedures on the selection and grant of livelihood assistance within the Municipality and adopt a system of monitoring and inspection of the projects; and


the Municipal Accountant be guided with COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 which provides for the Revised Chart of Accounts for the LGUs in the recording of transactions.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that:

The Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) together with all other employees concerned to (i) closely monitor the implementation of development projects and see to it that the priority projects identified in the Annual Investment Plan are promptly implemented in order to deliver satisfactory benefits to the constituents; and (ii) ensure that the reports on the status of government PPAs submitted to the Audit Team quarterly includes all on-going and planned PPAs for the year and that the information provided therein are accurate to facilitate proper monitoring and evaluation thereof;

The Municipal Engineer conduct appropriate detailed engineering activities to serve as basis of the MPDC in properly evaluating the technical viability of proposed projects before inclusion in the list of priority projects to be included in the 20 percent DF.  In this way, projects with issues, not feasible or has a remote possibility of being implemented may not be considered during the budget year;

The BAC ensure that all PPAs to be subjected for procurement are included in the Annual Procurement Plan pursuant to Section 7.2 of the 2016 Revised IRR of the R.A. No. 9184; and

The Municipal Accountant (i) be guided by the requirements of Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445, COA Circular No. 2012-001 and Section 474 b(5) of R.A. No. 7160 for proper documentation of claims against government funds; (ii) submit the lacking documents mentioned above to establish the propriety of the disbursements; and (iii) ensure that only disbursements charged against the 20 percent DF are recorded in its special journals.

Based on the foregoing audit observations, we recommended that the Bids and Awards Committee:

furnish the Audit Team with a copy of the Contract Agreement and its attachments within five calendar days from execution thereof as required under Section 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009;

observe strictly the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and GPPB Circular No. 04-2020 dated September 16, 2020 to ensure adherence to the principles of transparency, competitiveness and public monitoring;


strengthen internal control over the evaluation of bids and post-qualification of bidders; 


prepare the required documents/reports with extra care to avoid errors which could mislead reader and users of the said reports; and 



submit the lacking documents cited above to the Audit Team to comply with the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and address the deficiencies enumerated.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, thru the MSWM Focal Person:

prepare the necessary documents required for incorporation to LGUs Solid Waste Management Plan so as to obtain the National Solid Waste Commission’s approval on the said plan;

strictly enforce existing laws and ordinances on proper solid waste management;


fast track the processing of requirements for the establishment of a sanitary landfill in compliance with Sections 40 and 41 of R.A. No. 9003 the soonest possible time to avert adverse public health and environmental consequences; and


encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the Municipality within its level.

Based on the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

require the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to ensure the inclusion of duly appropriated COVID-19 related PPAs in the AIP of the Municipality in compliance with the provisions of the DILG - DBM JMC No. 02 dated March 30, 2020 and COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012;

render an explanation or justification on the following: (i) thru its OTAP coordinator, for failure to properly identify the specific items to be procured and included in the grocery packs to be distributed to various Odiongan households;  (ii) thru its HRMO, Municipal Accountant and MBO, on grant of Special Risk Allowance (SRA) and COVID-19 Hazard Pay to Barangay front line workers which are not in accordance with the computation provided in the afore-cited circulars; and (iii) thru its BAC, for use of Direct Contracting as alternative mode of procurement for the purchases of COVID-19 related PPAs;

require the BAC to observe strictly the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and other pertinent GPPB issuances in all its succeeding procurement activities during State of Emergency so as to avoid doubts on the integrity of its procurement; and

the Municipal Accountant to (i) review the regularity and completeness of supporting documents of disbursement vouchers before processing claims for payment; (ii) submit the lacking documents noted above; and (iii) observe the use of proper accounts in the recording of the financial transactions of the LGU.

