Based on the foregoing audit observations, we recommended and the management agreed that the Bids and Awards Committee:

a.	furnish the Audit Team with a copy of the Contract Agreement and its attachments within five calendar days from execution thereof as required under Section 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009;

b.	observe strictly the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to ensure adherence to the principles of transparency, competitiveness and public monitoring;

c.	strengthen internal control over the evaluation of bids and post-qualification of bidders;

d.	prepare the required documents/reports with extra care to avoid errors which could mislead reader and users of the said reports; and

e.	submit the lacking documents cited above to the Audit Team to comply with the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and address the deficiencies enumerated.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:

Conduct regular monitoring of the implementation of the plan and other relevant laws/ordinances within the Municipality’s jurisdiction to ensure the effectiveness of the solid waste management programs. Impose appropriate sanction where necessary;

Evaluate the current composition of the MSWMB and look for possible members that could qualify to complete the line up;

Strict enforcement of laws and ordinances on proper solid waste management;

Provide collectors and other personnel directly dealing with the collection of solid wastes with personal protective equipment to safeguard them from health hazards; and

Fast track the processing of various requirements for the operation of a sanitary landfill in accordance with Sections 40 and 41 of R.A. No. 9003 the soonest possible time to avert adverse environmental consequences.

We recommended that the Bids and Awards Committee: 

submit written explanation relative to the deficiencies noted above for evaluation of the Audit Team as to the next audit action;

submit the lacking documents noted above; 

strictly adhere to the provisions of 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 and other relevant rules and regulations governing the procurement of infrastructure projects. 

We also recommended that the TWG assess the sufficiency of the manpower and equipment capacity of the bidders prior to awarding the contracts. Disqualify all future bids whose key personnel and equipment were already pledged/used in other on-going projects or projects to be awarded to avoid unnecessary delays in project completion and to ensure quality project outcome. 
Further, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant review the supporting documents attached to the Disbursement Vouchers.

Based on the foregoing audit observations, we reiterated our previous recommendations that the Municipal Mayor:
require all accountable officers and employees to immediately liquidate their outstanding cash advances giving more emphasis to the long outstanding cash advances;
exert extra efforts to recover outstanding cash advances from Accountable Officers who are no longer in the service nor connected with the Municipality;
require strictly an Office Clearance from Money and Property accountabilities, pursuant to Sections 200 and 256, Vol. I of the Government Accounting and Auditing Manual from all personnel who seek retirement, resignation, transfer or claim for death benefits in order that all accountabilities could be appropriately settled;
direct the Municipal Accountant to refrain from granting additional cash advances to any official or employee unless previous cash advance given to him is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made, pursuant to Section 4.1.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; and
require the Municipal Accountant to maintain Subsidiary Ledgers and schedules for the accounts used for cash advances to facilitate monitoring of the amount outstanding per employee, to ensure that no additional cash advance will be granted to those with outstanding balances and to support the amounts reflected in the financial statements and submit same to the Audit Team.

We recommended that the GAD Council:
maintain GAD Database which will serve as the basis for planning, implementing and formulating GAD responsive activities pursuant to the provisions of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC 2013-01;
submit the Annual GAD Plan to the PPDO and DILG Regional Office, as appropriate, for review and approval.

We recommended that the Management:
ensure strict adherence to the provision of COA Circular No. 77-61 for the proper accounting and control of fuel consumption of government vehicles;
require the drivers of the motor vehicles to properly accomplish the daily trip tickets for each motor vehicle and ensure that the same is approved and signed by the end-user/passengers of the motor vehicle, be serially numbered and summarized at the end of the month in the Monthly Report of Official Travel and submitted to COA for audit purposes;
require the person in charge of the preparation of Fuel Consumption Report to present the relevant/necessary data stated in the above cited guidelines.

We recommended that the Management:
submit the MSWMP to the Provincial Solid Waste Management Board for review and for approval by the National Solid Waste Management Commission. Thereafter, review and update the plan as required by Law to ensure its sustainability, relevance and   effectiveness;
conduct regular monitoring on the implementation of the plan and other relevant laws within the Municipality’s jurisdiction to ensure the viability and effectiveness of the solid waste management programs;
encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of wastes. Impose appropriate sanction where necessary;
ensure that existing MRFs of the component barangays are fully functional and provide necessary support in enjoining the other barangay without MRF to establish the same;
